<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Describes Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0402100694 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0402100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> have agreed to take all necessary 
steps to boost India-German cooperation in industrial and 
technical fields. The two countries have agreed to set up an 
India-Germany joint mechanism to monitor progress in scientific 
cooperation. An official spokesman summing up the prime 
minister's visit to <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> said both the countries have also 
agreed to review the avoidance of double taxation treaty and 
pursue efforts to sign bilateral investment guarantees. Our 
correspondent Sudarshnam reports from <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>: 
  [Begin Sudarshnam recording] The Federation of German 
Industry and <ORGANIZATION>India-German Chamber of Commerce</ORGANIZATION> have sent 54 
proposals to intensify the economic relationship between the two 
countries. These relate to general and financial issues, 
pharmaceuticals and chemical industries, private sector and air 
traffic. As many as 40 ministries and departments in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> 
examined these proposals. Several of these have been 
implemented. Decision in respect of some are awaited. [end 
recording] 
  In another development, leading political parties of <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> 
have assured <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> that the <LOCATION>New Asia</LOCATION> concept initiated by 
Chancellor <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON> making <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> as a target country for 
intensified bilateral cooperation will be honored whichever 
party comes to power in this year's German elections. The 
assurance was conveyed to the prime minister, <PERSON>Mr. P.V. Narasimha 
Rao</PERSON>, when important German political leaders called on him in 
<LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> yesterday. An official spokesman said that there is a 
multiparty support to Chancellor <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON>'s <LOCATION>New Asia</LOCATION> concept, as 
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> has willingly recognized that <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in 
<LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> will be important political and economic powers in the 
years to come. The chief of the German Agency for Aid has 
shown his willingness to open a second window for soft credit to 
finance infrastructure projects in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. The projects include 
power and telecommunications sector. Meanwhile, the minister 
of state for external affairs, <PERSON>Mr. Salman Khurshid</PERSON>, who is 
accompanying the prime minister, has reiterated <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 
willingness to improve bilateral relations with <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>. He 
made it clear that <LOCATION>Islamabad</LOCATION> has no locus standi in <LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION>, and 
it is not in a position to advise <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in this matter. The 
minister said <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> has no problems regarding protection of 
human rights, and it is always ready to be open with 
international human rights organizations. 
  As reported, the prime minister is leaving for <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> today. 
He will meet the German president and address the <ORGANIZATION>Humboldt 
University</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> is also scheduled to have meeting 
with German business leaders and inaugurate the <ORGANIZATION>Indian Cultural 
Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>. On <DATE>Sunday</DATE> [6 <DATE>February</DATE>], <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> is 
returning home. Our correspondent Karuppaswamy reports that his 
meeting with German indologists and business leaders will be 
continuation of his earlier exprience in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> to reassure 
Germans that the reform process in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> is irreversible. The 
visit of the prime minister is the first official visit from 
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> to the reunited <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> -- the upcoming capital of the 
united <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>. 

</TEXT>

