<HEAD>Gandhi Returns to India After Patching Up Ties With China</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Tibetan protest. Pickup 3rd
graf `Gandhi told...'; SUBS 9th graf `New Delhi...' with graf to ADD
communique details on Tibet. Pickup 10th graf `India has...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> came home
<DATE>Friday</DATE> after five days in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and said his visit restored the
friendly Indian-Chinese relations of the early <DATE>1950s</DATE>.
   Also <DATE>Friday</DATE>, about 100 Tibetan students outside Parliament set
fire to a Chinese flag and denounced <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s recognition of <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION> as
part of <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>. Police with bamboo canes watched the rally but did
generally not interfere.
   Gandhi told a news conference at <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>'s international
airport, ``I believe this visit will be a new beginning for both
countries.''
   A border dispute has strained relations between <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>,
the world's two most populous countries, for nearly three decades.
<LOCATION>China</LOCATION> has more than 1 billion people, and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> has about 800
million.
   Gandhi's visit to <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> was the first by an Indian prime
minister since his grandfather, <PERSON>Jawaharlal Nehru</PERSON>, visited <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> in
<DATE>1954</DATE>.
   The two countries issued a communique in <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> earlier <DATE>Friday</DATE>,
agreeing to set up a joint working group to take up the territorial
dispute, which led to war in <DATE>1962</DATE>. <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> said the group would set a
time frame in which to resolve the issue.
   The communique also said Chinese Premier <PERSON>Li Peng</PERSON> has accepted an
invitation to visit <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>, but no date was set.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> claims 36,000 square miles of mountainous frontier that
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> says is part of its Arunachal Pradesh state. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> also says
<LOCATION>China</LOCATION> illegally occupies 14,500 square miles in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION>
state.
   Gandhi also told reporters that Chinese leaders respected <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s
views on <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>, another sore point in relations. <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> invaded
mountainous <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION> in <DATE>1949</DATE> and annexed it a year later.
   The communique noted that <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> ``expressed concern over
anti-China activities by some Tibetan elements in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>,'' and that
the Indian side had repeated its policy of recognizing <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION> as a
part of <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and banning Tibetans from carrying out anti-Chinese
political activities on Indian soil.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> has granted asylum to the <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>'s religious
leader, and thousands of his followers who fled <ORGANIZATION>Tibet</ORGANIZATION> after an
abortive uprising against Chinese rule in <DATE>1959</DATE>. <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> blames
supporters of the <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION> for pro-independence activities that
led to clashes with police in the last 14 months.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> signed three agreements _ a civil
aviation accord calling for direct flights between <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>, a three-year cultural agreement, and a science and
technology pact.
</TEXT>
