<H3> <TI>   Rao Discusses Bilateral Ties With Kohl in Berlin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0402062494 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0402062494 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> have expressed concern at the 
dangers posed by religious extremism. The prime minister, <PERSON>Mr. 
Narasimha Rao</PERSON>, and Chancellor <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON> called for immediate 
steps to check the spread of this threat. Briefing newsmen on 
the one-to-one talks between <PERSON>Mr. Rao</PERSON> and <PERSON>Dr. Kohl</PERSON>, an official 
spokesman said in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> that the two leaders discussed 
Indo-Pakistan relations. The prime minister reiterated that 
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> is in favor of peaceful relations with <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Mr. Rao</PERSON>, 
however, regretted that despite <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>'s efforts, the 
<LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> prime minister, <PERSON>Ms. Benazir Bhutto</PERSON>, has taken a 
strident view. Referring to the package of proposals offered by 
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> following the recent foreign secretary-level talks, <PERSON>Mr. 
Rao</PERSON> expressed the hope that continuance of worthwhile dialogue 
will yield positive results. During the talks, <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> promised to 
take steps to speed up access of German technology to <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. 
The German chancellor, <PERSON>Dr. Helmut Kohl</PERSON>, said bottlenecks, if 
any, will be removed. He promised to support <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in its 
dealings with the <LOCATION>European Union</LOCATION>. <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> has a prominent place 
in the <ORGANIZATION>Union</ORGANIZATION>. Our correspondent, <PERSON>S. Sudarshanam</PERSON>, understands 
that <PERSON>Mr. Rao</PERSON> spoke about human rights environment in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and 
the steps taken to protect and promote the human rights 
aspirations of the people. Earlier, the German foreign affairs 
minister, <PERSON>Dr. Klaus Kinkel</PERSON>, called on the prime minister. 
  The prime minister is visiting <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> later today. Our 
special correspondent, <PERSON>Karuppaswamy</PERSON>, reports: 
  [Begin Karuppaswamy recording] <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> is one of the very big 
cities in the world outside <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> with a full-fledged museum 
dedicated exclusively to Indian art. There are several streets 
named after <PERSON>Ravindranath Tagore</PERSON>, <PERSON>Jawaharlal Nehru</PERSON>, and <PERSON>Indira 
Gandhi</PERSON>. And <PERSON>Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose</PERSON> visited the city for 
the possible assistance during freedom struggle. <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha 
Rao</PERSON> will be received by the federal president, <PERSON>Dr. Richard Von 
Weizsacker</PERSON>. His engagements during his two days of visit to 
<LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> include a meeting with the governing mayor of the city, 
the German indologists, and representatives of the industry and 
commerce. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

