<HEAD>Gandhi Says India Will Not Interfere in Tibet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s
president, <PERSON>Yang Shangkun</PERSON>, today discussed <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s troubled region of
<LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>, and <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> said his country will not interfere in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s
internal affairs.
   The Indian leader spent much of his second day in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>
sightseeing.
   The official <ORGANIZATION>Xinhua News Agency</ORGANIZATION> said Yang explained <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s
position on <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Gandhi</LOCATION> during a one-hour meeting at the <PERSON>Great
Hall</PERSON> of the People.
   Yang, 81, who has held the largely ceremonial post of president
since <DATE>April</DATE>, stressed that the <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> government provides
assistance to the Tibetan region, one of <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s most backward areas.
   ``We respect the religious beliefs and customs and habits of the
Tibetan people, and they enjoy the freedom of religious belief,''
<PERSON>Yang</PERSON> said.
   Gandhi repeated <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s position that <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION> is an autonomous
region of <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and that <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> will not interfere in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s
internal affairs, <ORGANIZATION>Xinhua</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The Tibetan issue has long been a source of tension between the
two countries because <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> has provided refuge to the Tibetan
religious leader, the <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION>, and his followers, who have
demanded independence for <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION> fled to <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in
<DATE>1959</DATE> after he led a failed uprising against Chinese military forces.
   At least one Tibetan monk was shot and killed by Chinese security
forces during a demonstration in the Tibetan capital of <LOCATION>Lhasa</LOCATION> on
<DATE>Dec. 10</DATE>. It was the third outbreak of anti-Chinese violence in <LOCATION>Lhasa</LOCATION>
in the past 14 months.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> are trying to restore friendly ties after <DATE>a
quarter century</DATE> of soured relations, which hit bottom during a
21-day border war in <DATE>1962</DATE>.
   The border question was the main topic during talks <DATE>Monday</DATE>
between <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s Premier <PERSON>Li Peng</PERSON>.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> claims 36,000 square miles of what <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> says is part of
its northeast state of <LOCATION>Arunachal Pradesh</LOCATION>. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> claims 14,500 square
miles of land seized by <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> in <DATE>1962</DATE>.
   Gandhi and Li, however, vowed not to let the border problem
interfere with efforts to improve the strained bilateral ties.
   Gandhi is the first Indian leader to visit <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> since his
grandfather, former Prime Minister <PERSON>Jawalharlal Nehru</PERSON>, came in <DATE>1954</DATE>.
   Accomapnied by his Italian-born wife, <PERSON>Sonia</PERSON>, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> today
traveled about 37 miles northwest of <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> to the Badaling section
of the Great Wall, the 3,720-mile-long barrier built over a
2,000-year period to keep out invaders.
   The Indian leader also visited the <ORGANIZATION>Temple of Heaven</ORGANIZATION>, a 15th
century structure where <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s emperors once prayed for good
harvests and performed sacrificial rituals.
   On <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> is scheduled to meet 84-year-old senior
leader <PERSON>Deng Xiaoping</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party General</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>Zhao
Ziyang</PERSON>.
   The two sides are expected to sign agreements on civil aviation,
border trade, science and technology and the exchange of consular
offices in <LOCATION>Shanghai</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Bombay</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
