<H3> <TI>   Rao Says Industrial Climate `Extremely Good' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0402001394 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0402001394 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister has invited German businessmen 
to invest in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. Addressing the <ORGANIZATION>Indo-German Economic 
Conference</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> today, <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> described the 
industrial climate in the country as extremely good and 
favorable for investment. Making it clear that his government 
has absolutely no hesitation in going ahead with the economic 
liberalization process, <PERSON>Mr. Rao</PERSON> asserted that <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> will step up 
the reform process. He assured the German industry that there 
will be no constraints coming in the way. He added that 
constraints if any will be resolved by him and the German 
chancellor, <PERSON>Dr. Helmut Kohl</PERSON>. 
  Opening the conference, the chancellor, <PERSON>Dr. Kohl</PERSON>, assured 
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> of all possible assistance for the development of the 
industrial and technological cooperation. He said the economic 
policies of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> are on the right path. He told the conference 
that <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> with its reform-oriented economic policy is one of 
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>'s most important partners on the Asian continent. <PERSON>Dr. 
Kohl</PERSON> announced that both the countries have agreed to establish 
a high-level India-German commission for science and technology. 
The president of the <ORGANIZATION>Confederation of Indian Industry</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Mr. N. 
Godrej</PERSON>, asked <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> to remove the constraints and controls on 
technology transfer. 
  Our correspondent, <LOCATION>Sudarshanam</LOCATION>, reports from <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> that 
German 
industry has drawn up certain proposals for deregulating and 
liberalizing <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s economy. These proposals have been 
forwarded to the <ORGANIZATION>Indian Government</ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION>Indian Government</ORGANIZATION> after 
a study has sent certain recommendations. These are being 
examined to strengthen the economic and trade cooperation. Our 
correspondent understands that a German festival in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> will 
be held as soon as possible. 
  <PERSON>Mr. Rao</PERSON> was given a formal ceremonial welcome in the 
forecourt of the <ORGANIZATION>Federal Chancellor's Office</ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Mr. Rao</PERSON> 
inspected a guard of honor by the <ORGANIZATION>German Air Force</ORGANIZATION>. 
  Here is a report from our special correspondent A. 
Karuppaswamy: [Begin Karuppaswamy recording] The opening of the 
first India-German economic conference in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> by the German 
chancellor and <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> is another successful step 
towards the India-German cooperation. The event follows the 
successful dialogue between Indian and German industrialists 
since the prime minister's last visit in <DATE>1991</DATE>. The exchange of 
view and suggestions between the two delegates at the conference 
largely reflects the compelling necessity of both the nations to 
come closer to strengthen their bilateral ties in global 
interests. Modern <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> is viewed by Germans as a very valuable 
strategic partner in economic and scientific development because 
of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s ongoing reform-oriented economic policies aimed at 
liberalization offering one of the biggest markets in <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION>. [end 
recording] 
  That was a report from our special correspondent in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>. 
  Earlier, <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> held talks with the German 
minister for economic cooperation and development, <PERSON>Mr. 
Carl-Dieter Sprangar</PERSON>, and reaffirmed <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s commitment to 
closer cooperation with <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Mr. Rao</PERSON> also told German 
leaders that <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> is keen on enhanced trade and investment 
flow from <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>. 
  <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> has assured <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> that it will continue to take a 
neutral stance on the <LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION> issue. Kashmir figured 
prominently in the talks between the prime minister and the 
German leaders in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> explained the 
problems faced by <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> because of <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>'s abetment of 
terrorism in <LOCATION>Jammu</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Punjab</LOCATION>. He said, <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> is 
deliberately creating conditions to obstruct a meaningful 
dialogue. 

</TEXT>

