<HEAD>Gandhi In China: First Visit Of Indian Leader In 34 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> comes to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> <DATE>Monday</DATE> for the first
visit by an Indian prime minister since his grandfather, <PERSON>Jawalharlal
Nehru</PERSON>, made the trip 34 years ago.
   For <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON>'s nation and his political future, the stakes appear
high. For <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, little seemingly can go wrong.
   During a week long on symbolism but short on substance, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON>
will be feted in the capital, tour the ancient city of <LOCATION>Xian</LOCATION> and
visit <LOCATION>Shanghai</LOCATION>.
   The visit, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> recently said, will be ``very important ... for
this globe, for <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> and for both of us.''
   The two nations _ the world's most populous _ will probably sign
agreements on civil aviation, border trade and science and
technology, Indian and Western diplomats said, speaking on condition
of anonymity. <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> also may agree to establish consular
offices.
   But no substantial progress is expected on the critical issue of
their 2,400-mile border, over which the two countries fought a brief
war in <DATE>1962</DATE>.
   The two countries began border talks in <DATE>1981</DATE> but have made little
progress. <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> claims 36,000 square miles of Indian territory.
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> rejects the claim and demands that <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> return the 15,200
square miles it took in the <DATE>1962</DATE> war.
   Since then, relations have improved, but only slightly. The
border remains heavily guarded on both sides and bilateral trade,
which resumed in <DATE>1977</DATE> but amounted to only <MONEY>$150 million</MONEY> last year,
is limited.
   Both <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> say <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON>'s visit is intended to create an
atmosphere for greater communication and not to resolve the border
question. But Western diplomats said pressures on Gandhi could make
him more willing to compromise than his Chinese counterparts.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> is moving quickly to improve relations with the <LOCATION>Soviet
Union</LOCATION> after nearly three decades of hostility. A summit between
Soviet President <PERSON>Mikhail S. Gorbachev</PERSON> and Chinese leader <PERSON>Deng
Xiaoping</PERSON> may be held next year.
   Better Chinese-Soviet relations will eliminate <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION>'s need to
cultivate <LOCATION>New Dehli</LOCATION> as a foil against <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>. And by removing
tensions along its northern border, <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> will be under less
pressure to accomodate <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> on its southern flank.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> continues its close relationship with <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s
traditional enemy. <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>'s new prime minister, <PERSON>Benazir Bhutto</PERSON>, is
expected to visit <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> in <DATE>January</DATE> on her first official trip abroad.
   ``For <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON>, the whole visit has an air of him running along so
he doesn't get left out in the cold,'' said a Western diplomat in
<LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> who recently returned from <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>. ``For the Chinese, the
visit can't possibly go wrong.''
   A society that speaks with one voice when it comes to foreign
affairs, <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> has watched with apparent enjoyment as the Indian
press has pressured Gandhi to make progress on the border issue,
Western diplomats said.
   ``The prime minister has decided to stick yet another label to
his travel bags,'' wrote the normally pro-government Times of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>
in an editorial <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>. ``The more important question, however,
is, what is the prime minister going to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> for?''
   Gandhi also faces an election next year in which victory is far
from certain. Diplomats say he must convince his public that simply
establishing goodwill with the Chinese _ and not achieving a
dramatic breakthrough _ is a worthy goal.
   ``If he feels that he is failing at that, he might be persuaded
to do something rash,'' the Western diplomat said.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> could use the <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION>, the exiled Tibetan leader who has
taken refuge in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> since <DATE>1959</DATE>, to embarrass the Chinese. The
Tibetan refugees' parliament-in-exile on <DATE>Friday</DATE> called on <ORGANIZATION>Gandhi</ORGANIZATION> to
raise the issue of <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION> with Chinese leaders.
   But <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s hand is weakened by <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s apparent willingness to
crush dissent in <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>, regardless of international opinion. On <DATE>Dec.
10</DATE>, police shot and killed at least one monk in <LOCATION>Lhasa</LOCATION>, the capital
of <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>, during an anti-Chinese demonstration. In addition, <LOCATION>New
Delhi</LOCATION> also has backed <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s claims to the region.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> was one of the first non-socialist countries to recognize
<LOCATION>China</LOCATION> in the early <DATE>1950s</DATE>. Relations soured in the early <DATE>1960s</DATE> over
the border question and political disagreements.
   Relations improved slightly in the late <DATE>1970s</DATE>. <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> invited an
Indian leader to visit as early as <DATE>1979</DATE>, but <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> agreed to come
only in <DATE>November</DATE> of last year.
   Western diplomats say the timing of the acceptance was
significant because it came well after Sino-Soviet relations had
begun to improve.
</TEXT>
