<HEAD>Thorny Border Issue Dominates Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of New Delhi in grafs 3,5</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and Chinese
leaders spent most of their time together today discussing their
troubled border, the main issue dividing the world's most populous
nations, Indian journalists said.
   Gandhi also discussed <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION> and trade with his Chinese hosts.
   Gandhi and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s premier, <PERSON>Li Peng</PERSON>, met for two hours in the
morning following <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON>'s arrival from <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>. They continued
meetings after lunch, said the journalists who attended a news
briefing closed to non-Indian reporters.
   Gandhi's five-day visit marks the first time an Indian leader has
come to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> since <DATE>1954</DATE>, when his grandfather <PERSON>Jawalharlal Nehru</PERSON>
came to <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>.
   The last time Chinese and Indian leaders met was in <DATE>1960</DATE>, when
Premier <PERSON>Chou Enlai</PERSON> went to <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>. Two years later, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>China</LOCATION> fought a war over the border and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> occupied a large chunk
of Indian territory.
   Gandhi flew into <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> accompanied by about 100 top officials
and the two nations were expected to sign agreements on civil
aviation, border trade and science and technology.
   Consular offices in <LOCATION>Shanghai</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Bombay</LOCATION> may also be established.
   Little progress was expected on the 2,400-mile border.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Xinhua News Agency</ORGANIZATION> and Indian journalists said <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> and
Li agreed that the two nations had to find a way of settling the
border question peacefully.
   ``We should work now toward resolution of the border issue while
we work at the same time to expand and strengthen our bilateral
relations,'' the journalists quoted <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> as saying.
   Li said the border problem was hindering the two countries'
relations, <ORGANIZATION>Xinhua</ORGANIZATION> reported.
   Xinhua also said <PERSON>Li</PERSON> expressed ``admiration'' for <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s position
on <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>, a Chinese province bordering <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> has reiterated that <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION> is part of <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and forbids
Tibetan refugees in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> from engaging in political activities. In
<DATE>1959</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>'s leader, and thousands of Tibetan
refugees fled to <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> after an abortive, anti-Chinese uprising.
   On <DATE>Dec. 10</DATE>, at least one monk was killed in the Tibetan capital
of <LOCATION>Lhasa</LOCATION> during a clash between Chinese troops and Tibetans who seek
an end to 38 years of Chinese rule. It was the third bloody clash in
<LOCATION>Lhasa</LOCATION> in 14 months.
   Earlier <DATE>Monday</DATE>, at the <PERSON>Great Hall</PERSON> of the People in downtown
<LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> was given a 19-gun salute and met by Premier LI.
   Indian and Chinese flags lined <LOCATION>Tiananmen Square</LOCATION>, colored flags
lined the city's main boulevard, Changanjie.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> was one of the first non-socialist countries to recognize
Communist <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> soon after <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>'s <DATE>1949</DATE> revolution. In the early
<DATE>1960s</DATE>, relations deteriorated over the border question and personal
and political disagreements between Chinese leader <PERSON>Mao Tse-tung</PERSON> and
<ORGANIZATION>Prime Minister Nehru</ORGANIZATION>.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> now claims 36,000 square miles of Indian land. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>
rejects the claim and demands that <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> return the 15,200 square
miles it took in the war.
   In the late <DATE>1970s</DATE>, relations improved slightly when <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> began
emphasizing traditional state-to-state relations instead of
exporting socialist revolution.
   Direct trade resumed in <DATE>1977</DATE> but it amounted to just <MONEY>$150 million</MONEY>
in <DATE>1986-87</DATE> with few prospects for growth.
   The two countries began border talks in <DATE>1981</DATE> but have made little
progress in eight rounds.
   Interviews with Chinese scholars over the weekend found them
pessimistic about the possibility for good Sino-Indian ties. For
one, they said, the economies of the two countries are too similar
to allow for much trade.
   ``They export textiles and we export textiles. They want high
technology and we want high technology,'' said <PERSON>Zhang Minqiu</PERSON>, deputy
director of the <ORGANIZATION>Institute of South and Southeast Asian Studies</ORGANIZATION> at
<ORGANIZATION>Beijing University</ORGANIZATION>. ``We're competitors so we lack cooperative
spirit.''
   In addition, Chinese researchers said the border question appears
intractable.
   ``In some of the areas that we claim, the Indian government has
made big investments and has registered good economic growth,'' said
<PERSON>Ms. Zhang</PERSON>. ``It's very hard to see them giving it up.''
</TEXT>
