<H3> <TI>   Bonn Assures `Neutrality' on Kashmir </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0302070794 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0630 
GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0302070794 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> has assured <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> that it will continue to 
adopt a neutral stance on <LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION> and avoid making any value 
judgments in the matter. Kashmir figured prominently during the 
talks the prime minister, <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON>, had with the German 
leaders in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>. The prime minister explained to them the 
problems faced by <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> due to <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>'s abetment of terrorism 
in <LOCATION>Jammu</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Punjab</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> also 
apprised the German leaders of the serious threat posed to the 
country's unity and integrity from cross-border terrorism. The 
prime minister said <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> is deliberately creating conditions 
for not having a meaningful dialogue. He also informed them 
about the confidence-building measures his government had taken 
in the past toward good neighborly relations with <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>. 
  The issue also figured prominently during the foreign 
secretary-level talks in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>. The Indian side told the Germans 
about the setting up of the commission to look into the 
allegations of human rights abuses and permission given to the 
Amnesty International to visit the country. Attention was also 
drawn to the threat by <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> to move an anti-India resolution 
at the <LOCATION>Geneva</LOCATION> session on human rights. <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> sought 
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>'s help to thwart the attempt. Bonn assured that the 
anti-Indian motion on <ORGANIZATION>Kashmir</ORGANIZATION> will not serve any useful purpose. 
Both countries also called for wider representation in the <ORGANIZATION>UN 
Security Council</ORGANIZATION> to ensure the political effectiveness of the 
collective will of international community. Both <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> are aspirants of a permanent seat in the council. 

</TEXT>

