<HEAD>India's Gandhi Begins Border Talks with China</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Gandhi sightseeing on
Tuesday, CORRECTS spelling of Jawaharlal Nehru. PICKS up 8th pvs `It
is...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> put aside the
affairs of state for some sightseeing <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, a day after talks
with Chinese leaders on a border dispute and other issues that have
divided the world's two most populous nations.
   No breakthroughs were reported on the border issue, which led to
war in <DATE>1962</DATE>.
   Gandhi also discussed <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>, trade and the Cambodian conflict in
the <DATE>Monday</DATE> talks which his official spokesman described as ``warm,
cordial and very friendly.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Chinese Premier <PERSON>Li Peng</PERSON> and <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> met most of <DATE>Monday</DATE> following
<ORGANIZATION>Gandhi</ORGANIZATION>'s arrival from <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> for a five-day visit to <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Xian</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Shanghai</LOCATION>. Gandhi and his wife, <PERSON>Sonia</PERSON>, were later treated to
a state banquet at which Li acted as host.
   Gandhi's grandfather, <PERSON>Jawaharlal Nehru</PERSON>, was the last Indian
leader to travel to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, going to <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> in <DATE>1954</DATE>. Chinese and
Indian leaders last met in <DATE>1960</DATE>, when then-Premier Chou En-lai went
to <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>.
   On <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> toured the <ORGANIZATION>Temple of Heaven</ORGANIZATION>, a 15th century
structure where <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s emperors once prayed for good harvests and
performed sacrificial rituals.
   In the <TIME>afternoon</TIME>, he was to travel 40 miles northwest of <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>,
the capital, to the Badaling section of the Great Wall. The
3,720-mile-long barrier was built over 2,000 years to keep out
invaders from the north.
   Gandhi's only scheduled meeting <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> was with 81-year-old
President <PERSON>Yang Shangkun</PERSON>, a former senior army leader who took over
the largely ceremonial state post <DATE>last April</DATE>.
   On <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> is to meet 84-year-old senior leader <PERSON>Deng
Xiaoping</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party General</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>Zhao Ziyang</PERSON>.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> are expected to sign agreements on civil
aviation, border trade and science and technology. Consular offices
in <LOCATION>Shanghai</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Bombay</LOCATION> may also be established.
   In comments throughout <DATE>Monday</DATE>, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> and <PERSON>Li</PERSON> said Chinese-Indian
relations should follow a two-track policy of solving the border
dispute and improving other areas of their relationship.
   ``It is now time to look beyond the past,'' <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> said at the
banquet. ``It is now time to look forward to the future. It is now
time to restore the relationship between our two countries.''
   The pronouncements appeared to signal a change in Indian policy,
bringing it more in line with that of the Chinese. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> said in the
past it would improve Indian-Chinese ties only after progress was
made on the border.
   Western diplomats said last week that <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON>'s political worries
and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s external problems could have sparked the change.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> is improving its relations with the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> and
maintains strong relations with <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s traditional enemy
on its northeastern border.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s strong international position may have convinced <LOCATION>New
Delhi</LOCATION> to adopt a more conciliatory attitude to <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>, the
diplomats said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   At home, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> faces an election year next year in which victory
is by no means assured.
   Li also praised <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s position on the restive region of <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>,
which <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> recognizes as part of <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>.
   The Indian spokesman also said <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> and Li discussed <LOCATION>Cambodia</LOCATION>,
but he refused to elaborate. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> recognizes the current government
of <LOCATION>Cambodia</LOCATION>, which was installed by <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> after the <LOCATION>Hanoi</LOCATION>
government invaded the country in <DATE>December 1978</DATE>. <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> supports
Cambodian resistance groups.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> was one of the first non-socialist countries to recognize
Communist <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> soon after <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>'s <DATE>1949</DATE> revolution. In the early
<DATE>1960s</DATE>, relations deteriorated over the border question and political
disagreements. The border remains heavily guarded despite eight
rounds of Indian-Chinese talks on the question since <DATE>1981</DATE>, the last
of which took place in <DATE>November 1987</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> says <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> should return 15,200 square miles of territory
it took in the <DATE>1962</DATE> war.
</TEXT>
