<H3> <TI>   Companies Hope Indian Leader's Visit Stimulates Orders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102182694 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 1 Feb 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> AU0102182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<FÊP=106> [Report signed "sm": "Installation Constructers Hope for </F>
Large-Scale Orders"] 
  [Excerpts] <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>, 31 <DATE>January</DATE> -- Economic relations will be 
the focal issue of a four-day visit to <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION>Indian Prime 
Minister Narasimha Rao</ORGANIZATION> to begin on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> [2 <DATE>February</DATE>]. 
German companies hope this visit will support their efforts to 
get large-scale orders from <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. In return, <PERSON>Rao</PERSON> is working 
for German investment on the subcontinent. 
  One of the central issues of the talks in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> is the 
participation of German companies in expanding the power supply 
in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. This involves orders worth double-digit billion sums. 
Yesterday, <ORGANIZATION>Indian Energy Minister Salve</ORGANIZATION> explained to leading 
German installation constructors in <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> his government's plans 
for expanding the energy supply. According to him, new 
construction is planned of seven conventional power stations 
with a capacity of 5,500 megawatts and an investment of <MONEY>12 
billion German marks</MONEY>. In addition, seven existing power 
stations are to be modernized, that is, to be equipped with 
modern environmental technology. Furthermore, it is planned to 
expand <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s mains distribution. [passage omitted] 
  During his visit to <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Rao</PERSON> will take time for a 
"German-Indian economic conference," and for individual talks 
with the directors of <ORGANIZATION>Hoechst</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>BASF</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Mercedes</ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION>Siemens</ORGANIZATION> as 
well as with <ORGANIZATION>Volkswagen</ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON>Ferdinand Piech</PERSON>. 
  The political talks with Chancellor <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON>, Foreign 
Minister <PERSON>Klaus Kinkel</PERSON>, and <ORGANIZATION>Social Democratic Party</ORGANIZATION> Chairman 
<PERSON>Rudolf Scharping</PERSON> will focus primarily on coordinating a joint 
route toward the goal of the two countries getting permanent 
seats on the <ORGANIZATION>UN Security Council</ORGANIZATION>. The Germans will also be 
urging <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> to sign the <ORGANIZATION>Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty</ORGANIZATION>. 

</TEXT>

