<H3> <TI>   Rao Leads High-Level Delegation to U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rao Leads High-Level Delegation to U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Departs on 7-Day, 4-City Visit </H4>

<F P=102> BK1405101794 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0435 
GMT 14 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1405101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister, <PERSON>Mr. P.V. Narasimha Rao</PERSON>, has 
left <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> <TIME>this morning</TIME> for the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. He was seen 
off at the airport by his cabinet colleagues, chief ministers of 
<LOCATION>Andhra Pradesh</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Haryana</LOCATION>, and <PERSON>Madhya Pradesh</PERSON>, the governor of 
<ORGANIZATION>Uttar Pradesh</ORGANIZATION> and senior officials. The seven-day visit will 
take <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> to four cities, including the capital 
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> and will enable him to meet a broad segment of the 
<ORGANIZATION>Clinton Administration</ORGANIZATION>, congressmen, and business circles. 
  Our correspondent, <PERSON>M. Rama Rao</PERSON>, covering the visit, says the 
main thrust of the prime minister's talks will be on enhanced 
economic and investment cooperation between the two countries. 
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> will also reiterate its position on sensitive issues like 
Nuclear Nonproliferation, arms control, human rights, and 
<LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION> to the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> leaders. The Clinton-Rao talks slated for 
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> are expected to be open and frank, giving the leaders 
an opportunity to appreciate each other's point of view on world 
issues as also matters of mutual concern. 
  A high-level official delegation is accompanying the prime 
minister. It includes the finance minister, <PERSON>Dr. Manmohan Singh</PERSON>; 
the minister of state for external affairs, <PERSON>Mr. Salaman 
Khurshid</PERSON>; and the minister of state in the prime minister's 
office, <PERSON>Mr. Bhuvanesh Chaturvedi</PERSON>. A 21-member trade delegation 
drawn from the three apex bodies of Indian industry is also 
accompanying the prime minister to help forge enhanced Indo-U.S. 
economic relations. The highlights of the visit include an 
address by <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> to a joint meeting of the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. 
Congress</ORGANIZATION> and the lecture at the prestigious <ORGANIZATION>Harvard University</ORGANIZATION>. 

</TEXT>

