<HEAD>Tibetan Spiritual Leader and Nobel Winner Returns to India</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Tibetans threw flowers and
offered silk scarves in a tumultous welcome <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> for their
spiritual leader, the <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION>, who returned to his home-in-exile
with the <ORGANIZATION>Nobel Peace Prize</ORGANIZATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION> arrived at <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>'s international airport just
past midnight and was greeted by cheering men, women and children
from the 100,000-member Tibetan community exiled in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>.
   Inside the airport's arrival lounge, monks in maroon and saffron
robes lined up to welcome the 54-year-old <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION> with low bows
and traditional gifts of white scarves. Outside, thousands of
Tibetans lighted incense sticks and covered the roadway with
marigold and rose petals.
   ``I feel (the award) is recognition of my sincerest motivation
for nonviolent action,'' the leader of <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>'s resistance to
Chinese rule told reporters. ``I feel it may help to create more
awareness for the value of compassion and nonviolence.''
   When he was awarded the prize in <LOCATION>Oslo</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION>, on <DATE>Oct. 5</DATE>, the
<ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION> was in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> on one of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> visits he makes at
least twice a year to minister to Buddhist faithful and to heighten
international awareness of the Tibetan struggle. He spent four
weeks in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> on this trip.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION> fled to <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in <DATE>1959</DATE> after an abortive uprising
against the <DATE>1951</DATE> Chinese annexation of his remote Himalayan nation.
He has set up a government-in-exile in <LOCATION>Dharamsala</LOCATION>, an Indian town
300 miles north of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>.
   In recent months, he has dropped demands for complete Tibetan
independence and has proposed that <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> retain responsibility for
military and foreign policy.
   So far, there has been no concession by <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>. The <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>
government has said it is willing to discuss <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>. However, it
insists <ORGANIZATION>Tibet</ORGANIZATION> must remain an integral part of <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>.
   Asked whether his receiving the <DATE>1989</DATE> Nobel Prize could alter
<LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>'s stance, the <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION> said: ``At the moment, I don't
know. But after a few months you may see something.'' He did not
elaborate.
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> has condemned the award as an insult and interference in
its internal affairs.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Dalai Lama</ORGANIZATION>, dressed in the sleeveless robes of an ordinary
Buddhist monk and wearing a rosary on his left wrist, said he had
still not decided what to do with the award's <MONEY>$469,000</MONEY> cash prize.
   ``I may contribute something for the starving people in <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION>
or create an institution for world peace,'' he said. ``I need some
more ideas. I will speak to my colleagues.''
</TEXT>
