<H3> <TI>   Kohl, Indian Premier Discuss Economic Matters </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302132794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1224 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> (DDP/ADN) -- Chancellor <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON> has 
underlined the importance of economic relations between <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> 
and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. Kohl said <DATE>today</DATE> at the start of a German-Indian 
economic conference at the <LOCATION>Bonn Chancellery</LOCATION>, in the presence of 
Indian Prime Minister <PERSON>P. V. Narisimha Rao</PERSON>, that this conference 
underlined the "special importance" that the German Government 
attached to relations between the two countries. 
  Rao arrived in <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> for a two-day visit to <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> on 2 
<DATE>February</DATE>. Kohl welcomed the prime minister with military honors 
this morning at the <ORGANIZATION>Chancellery</ORGANIZATION>. Afterward they met for talks. 
Rao is also to visit <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> on the 4th and <DATE>5th February</DATE>. 
  At the economic conference, the chancellor said that 
relations between <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in the science and 
technology areas had always been very close and are 
characterized by cooperation in a spirit of trust on many 
projects. Kohl announced that it was agreed today to set up a 
high-level <ORGANIZATION>German-Indian Commission for Science and Technology</ORGANIZATION>. 
Mutual economic relations had developed "gratifyingly" in the 
past few years. Today, <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> was <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s second most 
important supplier and fourth most important market. German 
investments in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> were "considerable, but could still 
increase." 
  Rao welcomed German industry's Asian offensive. This project 
was appropriate to the positive economic developments in <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION>, 
he said. 
  The economic conference, the climax of <PERSON>Rao</PERSON>'s visit, was 
opened by <ORGANIZATION>Siemens</ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON>Heinrich von Pierer</PERSON>, the chairman of the 
<ORGANIZATION>Asia-Pacific Association</ORGANIZATION> of German industry. A large number of 
Indian and German business representatives took part in the 
conference. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

