<HEAD>Gandhi Arrives in China in First Such Visit in 34 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> arrived in the
Chinese capital <DATE>Monday</DATE> in the first visit to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> by an Indian
leader since his grandfather, <PERSON>Jawaharlal Nehru</PERSON>, came 34 years ago.
   Gandhi flew into <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> on a special <ORGANIZATION>Air India</ORGANIZATION> jet provided for
the trip. His usual plane remained in <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> because rats had
gnawed electrical cables in the aircraft.
   The five-day visit marks the first time the leaders of the
world's two most populous countries have met since <DATE>1960</DATE>, when
Premier <PERSON>Chou Enlai</PERSON> went to <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>. <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> has about 1.08 billion
people, and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> has about 880 million.
   Gandhi will meet with the communist government's leaders in
<LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>, tour the ancient city of <LOCATION>Xian</LOCATION> and visit <LOCATION>Shanghai</LOCATION>.
   On arrival at the airport, the Indian prime minister, wearing a
brown overcoat, was greeted by about 100 Indians who live in
<LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>. He made no statement to reporters.
   Before leaving his country, <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> said the visit will be ``very
important ... for this globe, for <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> and for both of us.''
   The two nations are expected to sign agreements on civil
aviation, border trade, and science and technology. Consular offices
in the Chinese city of <LOCATION>Shanghai</LOCATION> and the Indian city of <LOCATION>Bombay</LOCATION> may
also be established as a result.
   However, little progress is expected on the main issue dividing
the two countries, their 2,400-mile-long border. They fought a brief
border war in <DATE>1962</DATE>, and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> occupied about 15,000 square miles of
Indian territory that <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> still wants back.
   The two countries began border talks in <DATE>1981</DATE> but made little
progress in eight rounds.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> was one of the first non-socialist countries to recognize
Communist <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> soon after <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s <DATE>1949</DATE> revolution.
   In the early <DATE>1960s</DATE>, relations deteriorated over the border issue
as well as personal and political disagreements between Chinese
leader <PERSON>Mao Tse-tung</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Prime Minister Nehru</ORGANIZATION>.
   In the late <DATE>1970s</DATE>, relations improved slightly when <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> began
emphasizing traditional state-to-state relations, instead of
exporting communist revolution.
   Both Chinese and Indian officials say <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON>'s visit is intended
to create an atmosphere for greater communication _ not resolve the
border question.
</TEXT>
