<ACCESS> 06170240 </ACCESS>
<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: P.V. Narasimha Rao  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  INDIA; POLITICS  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The centrist Congress Party, winners of India's general election, sought today
to find coalition partners to form the next government.;    Senior Congress
leaders also have the task of finding a premier who won't cause a power
struggle in India, where elections had been delayed by the assassination of
former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  INDIA'S CONGRESS PARTY SEEKS COALITION PARTNERS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Nearly 300 people were killed during the campaign and the voting, making it
the most violent balloting since <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> gained independence 44 years ago.;   
The latest victim was a parliament candidate from <LOCATION>Punjab</LOCATION> state who was killed
<DATE>today</DATE> in a bomb blast in his home, Press Trust of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> reported.;   
Elections in <LOCATION>Punjab</LOCATION> are scheduled <DATE>Saturday</DATE> for both <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> and the state
legislature. Punjab was given a later date than the rest of this nation of 844
million people in order to bolster security measures.;    Sikh militias
campaigning for an independent nation have vowed to stop the elections. So far
they have killed three candidates for <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> and at least 19 for the state
legislature.;    The <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION>, which has ruled <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> for 40 years, will
dominate Parliament but was projected to fall about 40 seats short of the 256
needed for a majority, state-run television said.;    Small-party allies and
independents could give <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> an additional 20 supporters in the <LOCATION>Lok Sabha</LOCATION>,
or the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> of the People. It would, therefore, need to court coalition
partners among its political rivals.;    Party President <PERSON>P.V. Narasimha Rao</PERSON>
said <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> would try to choose its leader in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>. Rao spoke in the
drawing room of his <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> bungalow after meeting a half-dozen other party
bosses.;    The Indian Express newspaper <DATE>today</DATE> said <PERSON>Rao</PERSON> and regional leader
<PERSON>Sharad Pawar</PERSON> were in the running to be the next prime minister.;    Pawar is
the chief minister, the top elected official, of western <LOCATION>Maharashtra</LOCATION> state,
whose capital is <LOCATION>Bombay</LOCATION>. He was considered in a strong position because the
<ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> won 37 of the state's 47 parliamentary districts.;    "The
process of consultation is on, but we have nothing definite to offer," party
spokesman <PERSON>Pranab Mukherjee</PERSON> said <DATE>today</DATE>. "The election of the leader will have
to wait until all the results are declared.";    The counting is not expected
to be completed until Wednesday.;    With 438 of the 511 seats at stake
decided, the <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> won 213, television reported. Its small-party allies won
another 12. Partial returns from other districts showed the <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> would win
only about 15 of the remaining 73 seats, television said.  </TEXT>
