<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Rao Concludes U.S. Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Rao Concludes U.S. Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Returns to New Delhi </H4>

<F P=102> BK2305055494 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2305055494 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister returned to <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> <TIME>this 
morning</TIME> on the completion of his week-long visit to the <LOCATION>United 
States</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON> was received at the airport by the 
home minister, <PERSON>Mr. S.B. Chavan</PERSON>; the civil aviation and tourism 
minister, <PERSON>Mr. Ghlam Nabi Azad</PERSON>; and the Harayana chief minister, 
<PERSON>Mr. Bhajan Lal</PERSON>, besides others. 
  As reported the prime minister's arrival in <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> was 
slightly delayed as <ORGANIZATION>Air India</ORGANIZATION>'s special aircraft carrying him 
and his delegation developed a minor technical snag while 
landing at <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> for a scheduled halt. A standby aircraft 
already stationed at <LOCATION>Charles de Gaulle Airport</LOCATION> was used for the 
onward journey home. 
  India-American business leaders have proposed creating two 
new institutions on Wall Street in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> to chalk out 
programs for the modernization of Indian industry. Sponsored by 
the <ORGANIZATION>Greater Houston Partnership</ORGANIZATION>, the plan was presented to the 
finance minister, <PERSON>Dr. Manmohan Singh</PERSON>, who accompanied the prime 
minister, <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha Rao</PERSON>, on his just concluded <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> visit. 
A press release issued by the group says the plan envisages 
creating mutual funds, venture capital funds and other debt and 
equity instruments to raise capital for <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in the next 
decade. The release estimated a contribution of at least <MONEY>$100 
billion</MONEY> by the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> private industries for Indian markets in the 
next five years. It also said the Indian Americans have the 
capacity to fund <MONEY>$5 billion</MONEY> per year for the modernization of 
the country's industry. 
  The leader of the opposition in the <LOCATION>Lok Sabha</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Mr. Atal 
behari Vajpayee</PERSON>, has lauded the prime minister, <PERSON>Mr. Narasimha 
Rao</PERSON>, for not succumbing to <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> pressure on the issues of 
<LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty</ORGANIZATION>. Talking to 
newsmen in <LOCATION>Lucknow</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Mr. Vajpayee</PERSON> expressed satisfaction on the 
firm stand taken on these points. 

</TEXT>

