<HEAD>Soviet Leader Accuses U.S., Pakistan Of Blocking Geneva Accord On
Afghans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs with accusations against U.S., Pakistan,
quotes on Estonia, details. Pick up graf 4 pvs, `An estimated ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President <PERSON>Mikhail S. Gorbachev</PERSON>
today accused the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> of creating obstacles
in implementing the accord that provides for the withdrawal of <ORGANIZATION>Red
Army</ORGANIZATION> troops from <LOCATION>Afghanistan</LOCATION>.
   ``<LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> find it hard to accept new
approaches to international affairs,'' <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> said at a ceremony
where he received a peace prize named for former Prime Minister
<PERSON>Indira Gandhi</PERSON>.
   ``Their actions appear to indicate that they would like us to
rescind those accords, even though the grave consequences of that
are obvious,'' <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> said on the second day of his three-day
state visit to <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>.
   The <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> agreed in <DATE>April</DATE> to withdraw its estimated
100,000 troops from <LOCATION>Afghanistan</LOCATION>, and about half the troops have
left. Soviet troops entered in <DATE>December 1979</DATE> and have been helping
the Marxist government battle U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas.
   The <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Afghanistan</LOCATION> accuse <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> of continuing to
serve as a conduit for arms to the rebels in violation of the accord.
   Earlier today, <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> said a challenge by the Soviet republic
of <LOCATION>Estonia</LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION>Kremlin</ORGANIZATION> authority was part of the ongoing process of
``perestroika,'' or social change promoted by the Soviet leader.
<LOCATION>Estonia</LOCATION>'s parliament this week declared <LOCATION>Estonia</LOCATION> was sovereign and
has the right to veto Soviet laws.
   In his first public reaction to a rise of nationalism in the
<LOCATION>Baltic</LOCATION> republics of <LOCATION>Lithuania</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Latvia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Estonia</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> said:
``There is a lot of debate on how to approach the problem. I am sure
things will settle down.''
   The Soviet leader also said good relations between the <LOCATION>Soviet
Union</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> were necessary for peace in the Asia-Pacific
region.
   ``We are pleased to see signs of improvement in Indo-Chinese
relations,'' he said. ``Our own relations with <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> are also
evolving in an encouraging way.''
   ``Thinking of countries like the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>,
one is inevitably led to realize that good relations between them
are extremely important for the destinies of <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> and for global
progress.''
   Indian Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> is scheduled to visit <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>
next month, the first Indian head of government to visit the country
in 34 years. Chinese leader <PERSON>Deng Xiaoping</PERSON> is scheduled to visit
<LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION> early next year.
   Both <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> have had long-standing border
problems with <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> fought a brief war in <DATE>1962</DATE> over
the issue.
   <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON>'s comments on the unrest in the Baltic states were made
informally to reporters at a memorial to <PERSON>Mrs. Gandhi</PERSON>, which he
visited before the award ceremony.
   <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON>, accompanied by his wife, <PERSON>Raisa</PERSON>, placed a wreath of red
roses at <PERSON>Mrs. Gandhi</PERSON>'s memorial. He placed similar floral tributes
at memorials to her father and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s first prime minister,
<PERSON>Jawaharlal Nehru</PERSON>, and to <PERSON>Mohandas K. Gandhi</PERSON>, the hero of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s
freedom movement.
   An estimated 7,000 Afghan refugees, many of them opposed to
Soviet military involvement in their homeland, were confined to
their homes in <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> under police order for a second day. One
police officer said the order was issued to prevent any
embarrassment to the Soviet leader.
   The order asked Afghans not to ``move out of your residence till
21.11.88. ... Non-compliance of the order will render you liable for
prosecution.''
   The Afghans were also asked to report to nearest police stations
every morning for a head count, the officer said on condition of
anonymity.
   <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> has sought to dispel any doubts about the future of
Soviet-Indian relations. In an apparent reference to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>,
<PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> said ``the development of relations with third countries''
would not affect the <ORGANIZATION>Kremlin</ORGANIZATION>'s friendly ties with <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>.
   Both <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> have showed signs of easing
long-standing strains in relations with <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, prompting concerns
expressed by some Indian newspapers and some Indian officials about
shifts in the political balances in <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
