<H3> <TI>   Need To Improve Ties With U.S. Stressed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Need To Improve Ties With U.S. Stressed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0606142794 Calcutta ANANDABAZAR PATRIKA in Bengali 25 May 
94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> BK0606142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Calcutta ANANDABAZAR PATRIKA </F>
<F P=105>  Bengali </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FÊP=106> [By <PERSON>Suman Chattopadhya</PERSON>] </F>
  [Text] The Rao-Clinton joint news conference just 
concluded. When all of us were coming down the stairs of the 
<ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> after the conference, a young journalist from 
<LOCATION>Gujarat</LOCATION>, who was a member of the prime minister's entourage, 
loudly told a senior journalist from THE <LOCATION>WASHINGTON POST</LOCATION>, "Had 
this been our country then at least for the sake of courtesy, we 
would have asked your president some questions, but you have 
insulted our prime minister by not asking him any questions." 
The American journalist was not at all offended by this remark. 
He smiled and softly told the youth to come with his prime 
minister when he visits the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> after five years. He 
then added that at that time, you will not find us as 
indifferent. 
  This spontaneous anger of the unexperienced Indian 
journalist 
was 100 percent genuine. It is really difficult for 
professional Indian journalists to tolerate the disregard shown 
toward their prime minister by American journalists. This 
proves that American journalists do not give any importance to 
the country where about one sixth of the total world population 
lives. 
  <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> was able to create a lot of enthusiasm in the 
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> media during his first visit to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> in <DATE>1985</DATE>, 
but <ORGANIZATION>Narasimha Rao</ORGANIZATION> failed to generate even a fraction of that 
enthusiasm. The major <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> newspapers gave wide coverage to the 
press conference which was addressed by <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> at the 
<ORGANIZATION>National Press Club</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>. This time, the newspapers 
thought it a waste to spare space to cover Rao. During <PERSON>Rajiv 
Gandhi</PERSON>'s visit, THE <LOCATION>NEW YORK</LOCATION> TIMES criticized the <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> 
administration for trying to impress Gandhi by showing robots to 
him. The newspaper said "<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> must be reckoned with in deeper 
terms than by displaying robots or space capsules to as 
sophisticated a man as <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON>." This time, due to the 
request made by the <ORGANIZATION>Indian Embassy</ORGANIZATION>, only THE <LOCATION>WASHINGTON</LOCATION> POST 
agreed to write a short report on <PERSON>Rao</PERSON>'s visit. It wrote: "A 
small bald figure in a <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> grey suit, a man with a 
shy manner and a low voice, a man who is a total stranger to the 
(?sound bite) [as published], the Indian prime minister is not 
easily recognizable as a politician." It is unfortunate for the 
senior, learned, and experienced prime minister of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> that 
popular television networks like <ORGANIZATION>NBC</ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION>ABC</ORGANIZATION> did not feel it 
necessary to give even one minute's coverage to him. 
  Did Rao really deserve the neglect which was shown him by 
the 
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> media? <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON> was able to attract American 
journalists due to his amiable disposition, westernized outlook, 
and alluring personality. Rao had something valuable in his 
pocket which the Americans should have been attracted to, that 
is, a market economy. The media did not give much importance to 
<ORGANIZATION>Narasimha Rao</ORGANIZATION> this time as they are not very aware of the 
developments which are taking place in the Indian subcontinent. 
Despite this, there is no denying the fact that <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> will soon 
become very important to the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> media just as <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> has 
become. The <PERSON>Clinton</PERSON> administration was reluctant to give most 
favored nation treatment to <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> as its human rights record 
was not satisfactory. This enraged the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> media. The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> 
media is of the opinion that nothing should be done which would 
hamper bilateral trade ties with <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>. 
  Americans continuously shed tears for the cause of 
democracy, 
but why is the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> media so keen to keep the communist 
dictators of <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> happy. This is so because their only 
objective is trade. If <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> does not get most favored nation 
status due to the rashness of <PERSON>Clinton</PERSON>, then <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> industrialists 
will be affected and the interests of the country will be 
hampered. Their main objective is to protect the economic 
interests of the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. It should be achieved at any 
cost even if it is necessary to renounce the country's policies. 
It has been observed that <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> did not make any special 
efforts to secure most favored nation status. The industrial 
corporations and the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> media are working together to protect 
the interests of the Chinese leaders, <PERSON>Deng Xiaoping</PERSON> and <PERSON>Li Peng</PERSON>. 
  <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> will also be able to acquire this importance after 
the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> becomes involved in its market. The first and 
foremost requirement is to attract <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> capital. During his 
visit to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, to some extent <ORGANIZATION>Narasimha Rao</ORGANIZATION> has 
been able to attract <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> businessmen to <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. This is the 
most significant aspect of his visit to that country. These 
people were able to realize the amount of profit they can make 
by investing in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. It is true they have been impressed by 
the reform measures initiated by <PERSON>Rao</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Manmohan</ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> 
businessmen have started realizing that this country of hermits 
and snake charmers have a middle class population of about 200 
million people, who have great purchasing power. There was no 
one in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> to speak in favor of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in the past. 
At present, a lobby of industrialists has been formed in favor 
of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. Some key persons of giant <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> corporations have also 
joined this group. A new horizon of prospects has been created 
in front of their eyes -- the largest free market of the 21st 
century. 
  Their eagerness towards this country is new and it must be 
admitted that <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> will gain from it. The first benefit is 
economic. This is because <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> is desperately in need of 
foreign capital, particularly in the sphere of infrastructure. 
The second gain is political. Due to growing <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> interests in 
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, other sensitive political issues like <LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION> and the 
nonproliferation issue will gradually lose significance. 
President <PERSON>Clinton</PERSON> and his colleagues did not make any attempt 
to embarrass Rao on these issues during his recent visit. The 
main reason behind this is pressure from industrialists. If the 
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> remains passive on these issues, then <LOCATION>Islamabad</LOCATION> 
will have to suffer. In fact, it is the intention of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> to 
blunt the sharp mouth of <LOCATION>Islamabad</LOCATION>. 
  To sum up, it may be said that in this post Cold War era, it 
is essential to improve ties with the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. It is 
necessary to play the economic card well to establish this 
relationship. <ORGANIZATION>Narasimha Rao</ORGANIZATION>'s visit has created prospects for 
the establishment of friendly relations between the two 
countries. This relationship will be further strengthened if 
the pledges given by <PERSON>Rao</PERSON> and Manmohan regarding economic reforms 
are speedily implemented. Once capital is invested in this 
country, then it is bound to influence the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> and the 
